# Development Workflow

## Version Control (Git)

- Write clear, conventional commit messages (`fix:`, `feat:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`).
- Keep commits small and atomic — one logical change per commit.
- Use feature branches; never push directly to `main`/`master`.
- Tag releases and maintain a changelog.

## Research & Reuse (before building)

- Prefer reusing existing patterns in this repo before adding new ones.
- Confirm library usage and version-specific behavior via primary docs (and Context7 when available).
- Prefer battle-tested libraries over hand-rolled utilities when they meet the need.

## Code Reviews

- All changes go through Pull Requests — no exceptions for production code.
- PRs should be small enough to review in one sitting (< 400 lines preferred).
- Reviewers check for correctness, readability, test coverage, and security.
- Use pair programming for complex or high-risk changes.

## Test-First (when practical)

- For new behavior and bug fixes, prefer a tight red/green/refactor loop to avoid regressions.
- Do not “fix” flaky tests by weakening assertions; make tests deterministic.

## CI/CD

- Every PR must pass automated builds, linting, and tests before merge.
- Deploy in small, safe batches — prefer frequent small releases over big-bang deploys.
- Automate everything repeatable: builds, tests, deploys, database migrations.
- Maintain rollback capability for every deployment.

